<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>AFC 95908 - Radiator</stitle>
    <afc id="AFC95908">
        <afcnum>95908</afcnum>
        <afcdate>May, 1995</afcdate>
        <subjectfile>ENGINE</subjectfile>
        <subject>Radiator</subject>
        <apply>
            <configure>
                <truckmodelgroup/>

                <truckmodel>3000
                    <daterange>
                        <enddate>12/12/1994</enddate>
                    </daterange>
                </truckmodel>
            </configure>
        </apply>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <para>The radiator support assembly in 3900FC and 3000 FE bus chassis built prior to December 12, 1994
                    can develop fatigue cracks in the lower corners. To prevent this from occurring, a mastic compound
                    is to be installed in the lower corners.
                </para>
            </geninfo>
        </description>
        <partsinfo>
            <para>Use mastic compound Sikaflex 255FC or Essex U418 (quick curing primerless auto glass urethane
                adhesive). These can be purchased from auto glass suppliers or retailers. Nozzles may need to be
                purchased separately.
            </para>
        </partsinfo>
        <svcproc svcproctype="afcrepair" graphiccount="3">
            <title>SERVICE PROCEDURE</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Allow radiator to cool to room temperature.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clean areas on radiator and horsecollar where mastic compound is to be installed (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9590801">Figure 1</hotlnk>) with a quick drying parts cleaner such as CRC Brakleen.
                </para>
                <figure id="f9590801" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g9590801" filename="../afcfigures/g9590801.webp" type="webp" resolution="300"/>
                    <caption>Figure 1.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Cut the dispensing tube nozzle so that the opening is approximately 5/16 inch in
                    diameter.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use plastic gloves to prevent compound from coming in contact with skin.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a heavy duty caulking gun to apply one tube of mastic to each radiator (one half in
                    each lower corner) (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9590802">Figure 2</hotlnk>
                    and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9590803">Figure 3</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f9590802" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g9590802" filename="../afcfigures/g9590802.webp" type="webp" resolution="100"/>
                    <caption>Figure 2.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f9590803" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g9590803" filename="../afcfigures/g9590803.webp" type="webp" resolution="100"/>
                    <caption>Figure 3.</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>For ease of application, the mastic compound should be at least 70 degrees F.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Mastic should be applied for the full thickness (front to back) of the radiator, from
                    the lowest horsecollar bolt to halfway down the side of the lower radiator tank.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Allow to cure 30 minutes before starting engine.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
        <laborinfo>
            <para>Operation number must appear on all claims.</para>
            <table id="labortab" frame="all">
                <tgroup cols="3" colsep="1" rowsep="1">
                    <colspec colwidth="1.56in"/>
                    <colspec colwidth="2.85in"/>
                    <colspec colwidth="1.08in"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row>
                            <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                <para>Operation No.</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                <para>Description</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                <para>Time</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                <para>A40-95908-1</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                <para>Apply mastic compound to radiator</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                <para>0.7 hour</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
        </laborinfo>
        <claims>
            <para>Expense is to be charged to Warranty. Claims are to be submitted in the normal manner, making
                reference to
                <hotlnk xrefid="afcclaim">Authorized Field Change</hotlnk>
                Number G-95908.
            </para>
            <figure id="afcclaim" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="afclaim" filename="../afcfigures/afclaim.webp" type="webp"/>
            </figure>
            <para>It is important that the coding be completed properly to assist in processing the warranty claim.
                Complete instructions will be found in the Warranty Manual, Section 7-1. Special attention should be
                given to items 39 through 44.
            </para>
            <para>To assure this important improvement is made in a timely manner, all claims for G-95908 activity must
                be submitted by May 31, 1996, or within the normal warranty period for the vehicle, if after May 31,
                1996.
            </para>
        </claims>
    </afc>
